Dynamic storage:
A pods cant manage storage directly, it can do it through CSI (Container Storage Interface) which can talk to a storage provider directly with a provisioner. 
dynamic storage workflow:
PVC
 ↓
StorageClass (defines the rules of creating storage)         
 ↓
CSI Dynamic Provisioner
 ↓
PV
 ↓
Pod

Resource allocation: 
for a namespace, requests and limits of memory and CPU would be defined; and for an application, requests and limits of memory would be defined, requests of CPU would be defined, BUT 
limits of CPU shouldnt be defined. because redundant memory will be given back to the resource pool, but redundant CPU will not be given back to the CPU pool. 

Resource quota: 
to avoid requests and limits of CPU and memory in every deployment 
it's a concept on a project level (namespace in OpenShift), not at the pod level. It limits the total resources such as pods in a namespace.

catalog:
a template can be created and customised by creating a yaml file with kind: Template, then $ oc create -f <file-name>.yaml
to develop the yaml contents for a service, $ oc export service db, which would export the yaml configuration for the service, which can be used to create a template
after creating the template, a catalog item can be created for it
